    {
        "content": "<p>The nlab page (<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/sylleptic+monoidal+2-category\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/sylleptic+monoidal+2-category</a>) is rather sparse.</p>\n<p>What does it mean for a transformation to be \"in-between\" a symmetry and a braiding? What kind of generalized string (surface maybe?) diagrams do they form? What dimension does it naturally occur in (if we consider braidings to occur in 3D space, and symmetries to occur in 4D space)? To my brain used to 3D Euclidean space, the idea throws me a loop. Can a syllepsis be visualized?</p>\n<p>Generalizing up, is there a kind of monoidal 4-category that has transforms that are in between a syllepsis and a braiding, or are they in between being a syllepsis and a symmetry? Is this an open question?</p>",
        "id": 492644829,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Elliott Peterson",
        "timestamp": 1736405011
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Larry Breen, James Dolan and I thought about up these ideas as part of the \"periodic table of n-categories\".    You can definitely visualize what's going on if you work at it.</p>\n<p>The reason braided monoidal categories are relevant to 3d space is that in 3d space one piece of string can cross another in two different ways: over or under.   These are the braiding</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></msub><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> B_{x,y} : x \\otimes y \\to y \\otimes x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>and the inverse braiding</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> B^{-1}_{y,x} :  x \\otimes y \\to y \\otimes x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1972em;vertical-align:-0.3831em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.453em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3831em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>In 4d space this distinction goes away because there's enough room to continuously deform one of the crossings to the other.  Thus, we get symmetric monoidal categories, where</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> B_{x,y} =  B^{-1}_{y,x} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9694em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1972em;vertical-align:-0.3831em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.453em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3831em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>However, a 2-categorical viewpoint goes deeper.   In 4d space there are <em>two fundamentally different ways</em> to continuously deform one of the crossings to the other: we can push one of the strings a bit 'up' into the 4th dimension, or 'down'.    Either deformation gives an <em>2-isomorphism</em> </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></msub><mo><mover><mo><mo>⇒</mo></mo><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∼</mo></mover></mo><msubsup><mi>B</mi><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> B_{x,y} \\stackrel{\\sim}{\\Rightarrow}  B^{-1}_{y,x} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2098em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9237em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⇒</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.5669em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∼</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1972em;vertical-align:-0.3831em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.453em;margin-left:-0.0502em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">,</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3831em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>If we pick one of these, we can call it the <em>syllepsis</em>.</p>",
        "id": 492659177,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736410541
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In 4d space the syllepsis and the 'inverse syllepsis' are different.  When we go two 4d space there is a 3-isomorphism between them... but in fact there are two.   And so on: the pattern keeps repeating itself.   This is a way to think about why the periodic table has the zig-zag shape it does<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/fKLLTtHQKhntnvSoDWDDpQQU/periodic_table.jpg\">:</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/fKLLTtHQKhntnvSoDWDDpQQU/periodic_table.jpg\" title=\":\"><img data-original-dimensions=\"829x769\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/fKLLTtHQKhntnvSoDWDDpQQU/periodic_table.jpg/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 492659850,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736410779
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This chart shows just 3 columns, but there are infinitely many columns and the pattern keeps going on.</p>",
        "id": 492659955,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736410807
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the last paragraph did you mean a 3-isomorphism when we go to 5d space?</p>",
        "id": 492787979,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1736446556
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/What.20exactly.20is.20a.20sylleptic.20monoidal.202-category.3F/near/492659177\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Larry Breen, James Dolan and I thought about up these ideas as part of the \"periodic table of n-categories\".    You can definitely visualize what's going on if you work at it.</p>\n<p>[...]</p>\n<p>If we pick one of these, we can call it the <em>syllepsis</em>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why was the name <em>syllepsis</em> chosen?</p>",
        "id": 492812237,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Elliott Peterson",
        "timestamp": 1736454559
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"609515\">Kevin Carlson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/What.20exactly.20is.20a.20sylleptic.20monoidal.202-category.3F/near/492787979\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In the last paragraph did you mean a 3-isomorphism when we go to 5d space?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I seem to have been falling asleep: \"When we go two 4d space\" should have been \"When we go to 5d space\".</p>",
        "id": 492822411,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736458343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"389450\">Keith Elliott Peterson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/What.20exactly.20is.20a.20sylleptic.20monoidal.202-category.3F/near/492812237\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Why was the name <em>syllepsis</em> chosen?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In our <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/q-alg/9503002\">original paper introducing the periodic table of n-categories</a>, James and I called them \"weakly involutory 2-categories\".   But \"involution\" means too many things, so later <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0001870897916492?via%3Dihub\">Ross Street</a>, who has a way with words, called them \"sylleptic monoidal 2-categories\".   </p>\n<p>Syllepsis is a <a href=\"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/syllepsis\">real word</a> that has something to do with the number 2.   It comes from the Greek word <em>syllēpsis</em>, which means \"a putting together\".  But I don't think either of these really justify its new use in math.  Probably the fact that it sounds like \"symmetric\" is the key here: in the category column of the periodic table we have</p>\n<p>monoidal, braided, symmetric</p>\n<p>while in the 2-category column we have</p>\n<p>monoidal, braided, sylleptic, symmetric.</p>\n<p>I'm glad to see Wikipedia has <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeugma_and_syllepsis\">an article distinguishing syllepsis from zeugma</a>.  You wouldn't want to get those mixed up!  <span aria-label=\"crazy\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f61c\" role=\"img\" title=\"crazy\">:crazy:</span></p>",
        "id": 492824005,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736458924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wouldn't be surprised if Ross consulted with Max Kelly on the Greek...</p>",
        "id": 492872755,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1736481756
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a name for the new kind of monoidal tricategory that appears between sylleptic and symmetric yet? Perhaps it should be zeugmatic, to be rather impishly indifferent to the actual meaning of the words.</p>",
        "id": 493002926,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1736533295
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>At that point I'd probably just start saying \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E_4</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0576em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">4</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>\".</p>",
        "id": 493003444,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1736533502
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say \"quadruply monoidal\", but even this doesn't scale well.   However, I <em>do</em> like the idea of using \"zeugma\" in mathematics: it's as scary as \"syzygy\" and \"plethysm\".   <span aria-label=\"smiling imp\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f608\" role=\"img\" title=\"smiling imp\">:smiling_imp:</span></p>",
        "id": 493005234,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736534171
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think I will just stick with 4-tuply monoidal 3-category (assuming a \"zeugma monoidal 3-category\" is just 4-tuply monoidal 3-category, and a sylleptic monoidal 3-category is a 3-tuply monoidal 3-category).</p>\n<p>You can't make me learn Greek!</p>",
        "id": 493128280,
        "sender_full_name": "Keith Elliott Peterson",
        "timestamp": 1736630343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But you should at least say \"zeugmatic\" if you're going to use \"zeugma\" as an adjective.</p>",
        "id": 493128583,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1736630641
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"Zeugmoidal\" <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
